    "informal_statement": "Let \(P,Q\) be probability measures on \((X,\\mathcal{F})\) with \(P\\ll Q\). Then \[D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge 2\\,\\|P-Q\\|_{\\mathrm{TV}}^2.\]",
    "informal_proof_text": "Set \(\\delta:=\\|P-Q\\|_{\\mathrm{TV}}\). By the Hahn decomposition of \(P-Q\), choose \(A\\in\\mathcal{F}\) with \(P(A)-Q(A)=\\delta\\ge 0\). Define the measurable map \(T:=\\mathbf{1}_A:X\\to\\{0,1\\}\) and let \(p:=P(A)\), \(q:=Q(A)\), so \(T_\\#P=(p,1-p)\) and \(T_\\#Q=(q,1-q)\). By the data-processing inequality (DPI), \[D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)=p\\log\\!\\left(\\tfrac{p}{q}\\right)+(1-p)\\log\\!\\left(\\tfrac{1-p}{1-q}\\right).\] By the Bernoulli scalar inequality applied with \(p-q=\\delta\), the right-hand side is \(\\ge 2(p-q)^2=2\\delta^2\). Hence \(D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge 2\\delta^2=2\\|P-Q\\|_{\\mathrm{TV}}^2\)."
  },
  {
    "id": "dpi",
    "title": "Data-processing inequality for KL divergence",
    "display_label": "DPI: $D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q)$",
    "informal_statement": "Let \(P,Q\) be probability measures on \((X,\\mathcal{F})\) with \(P\\ll Q\), and let \(T:(X,\\mathcal{F})\\to(Y,\\mathcal{G})\) be any measurable map. Then \[D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(T_\\#P\\|T_\\#Q),\] where \(T_\\#P\) and \(T_\\#Q\) denote the pushforward measures on \((Y,\\mathcal{G})\).",
    "informal_proof_text": "This is the standard data-processing / information-monotonicity property of relative entropy. Intuitively, applying a measurable map \(T\) coarsens the \(\\sigma\)-algebra and can only reduce the amount of information separating \(P\) from \(Q\). Formally, it follows from Jensen's inequality applied to the log-sum inequality, or from the chain rule for KL divergence and non-negativity of conditional KL. In the binary pushforward case \(T=\\mathbf{1}_A\) the inequality becomes \[D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(P\\|Q)\\ge p\\log\\!\\left(\\tfrac{p}{q}\\right)+(1-p)\\log\\!\\left(\\tfrac{1-p}{1-q}\\right),\] where \(p=P(A)\) and \(q=Q(A)\)."
  },
